        "subject": "LU-6397 osc: Remove kms_valid check in osc_enqueue",
        "message": "LU-6397 osc: Remove kms_valid check in osc_enqueue\n\nIf kms_valid is not set in osc_enqueue_base, a new lock\nrequest will not attempt to match existing ldlm locks.\n\nThis opens up a race on newly created objects where a\nclient can create two LDLM lock requests where only one\nis necessary:\n\nkms_valid is not updated until osc_enqueue_fini is called,\nwhich does not happen until a lock request has received a\nreply from the server.\n\nConsider two processes, P1 and P2:\nP1 makes an IO request (FX, write first page of a file)\nP1 creates an LDLM lock request\nP1 does not check for existing LDLM locks because kms_valid\nis not set\nP1 waits for reply from server\nP2 makes an IO request (FX, read second page of the file)\nP2 creates an LDLM lock request\nP2 does not check for existing LDLM locks (goto(no_match) i\nP2 waits for a reply from server\nP1 Receives reply, lock is granted\n(Lock is expanded beyond the requested extent, so it covers\nthe area P2 wants to read)\nP2 Receives reply, lock is blocked by lock granted to P1\nLock granted to P1 is called back by server, even though it\nmatches request from P2\n\nkms_valid is checked here because it is currently possible\nto have ldlm locks without a corresponding osc object if\nthe osc object has been destroyed by osc_object_prune.\n(Called for drop_caches or under memory pressure.)\n\nThis patch changes osc_object_prune to cancel any LDLM\nlocks associated with that osc object.  This is safe\nbecause if any of the LDLM locks are in use, the\nosc object will not be a candidate for pruning.\n\nThis allows us to remove the kms_valid check in\nosc_enqueue_base.\n\nSigned-off-by: Patrick Farrell <paf@cray.com>\nChange-Id: Ic1f73d82e6fbaf4adcac594d1f831782168f7a59\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
    }
